1
00:00:00,640 --> 00:00:02,399
The Cozy English.

2
00:00:02,399 --> 00:00:04,420
Learn English slowly.

3
00:00:05,259 --> 00:00:09,299
Hello, dear friends, and welcome back to the Cozy English.

4
00:00:09,419 --> 00:00:12,899
I'm Emma, and I'm so glad you're here with us again.

5
00:00:12,935 --> 00:00:13,995
Hi, everyone.

6
00:00:13,995 --> 00:00:15,055
I'm Daniel.

7
00:00:15,095 --> 00:00:18,895
You know, Emma, I've been thinking a lot about today's topic.

8
00:00:18,854 --> 00:00:20,314
It's kind of serious.

9
00:00:20,314 --> 00:00:20,975
Right?

10
00:00:21,095 --> 00:00:24,815
It is, but it's also important.

11
00:00:25,095 --> 00:00:29,639
Today, we're talking about something that touches everyone, time.

12
00:00:29,840 --> 00:00:34,920
More exactly, how not to waste it, because we're not young forever.

13
00:00:35,440 --> 00:00:37,800
That sounds a little scary.

14
00:00:39,120 --> 00:00:40,040
Maybe.

15
00:00:40,160 --> 00:00:41,640
But think of it this way.

16
00:00:41,785 --> 00:00:45,185
Time is the most precious gift we have.

17
00:00:45,385 --> 00:00:47,005
We can earn more money.

18
00:00:47,005 --> 00:00:51,665
We can buy more things, but we can never buy back time.

19
00:00:51,625 --> 00:00:52,945
That's true.

20
00:00:52,905 --> 00:00:56,464
Sometimes I feel like days just disappear.

21
00:00:56,960 --> 00:01:02,200
I wake up, do a little work, check my phone, and suddenly it's evening.

22
00:01:02,320 --> 00:01:03,540
Yes.

23
00:01:03,540 --> 00:01:05,319
I know that feeling too.

24
00:01:05,280 --> 00:01:08,919
It's almost like sand slipping through our fingers.

25
00:01:08,960 --> 00:01:11,399
We don't notice until it's gone.

26
00:01:12,105 --> 00:01:17,585
So the real question is, how do we use our time well?

27
00:01:17,865 --> 00:01:19,425
That's the heart of it.

28
00:01:19,385 --> 00:01:23,585
We use it by remembering that every hour is valuable.

29
00:01:24,280 --> 00:01:32,479
Even simple moments, like talking with a friend, learning something new, or just enjoying a walk, are treasures.

30
00:01:32,760 --> 00:01:35,280
I like that word, treasures.

31
00:01:35,875 --> 00:01:40,454
It makes me think that even small things in daily life can be meaningful.

32
00:01:40,454 --> 00:01:41,434
Exactly.

33
00:01:41,795 --> 00:01:43,734
And here's something I've noticed.

34
00:01:43,734 --> 00:01:47,755
When we see time as treasure, we live more carefully.

35
00:01:48,270 --> 00:01:49,829
We choose better.

36
00:01:50,030 --> 00:01:53,829
We don't let our hours just disappear without meaning.

37
00:01:54,030 --> 00:01:55,829
That makes sense.

38
00:01:55,870 --> 00:02:01,429
I guess I need to ask myself, am I spending time, or am I investing it?

39
00:02:01,390 --> 00:02:02,949
Beautifully said, Daniel.

40
00:02:03,355 --> 00:02:07,235
Spending means it's gone with nothing to show.

41
00:02:07,595 --> 00:02:14,435
Investing means it grows into something, skill, joy, love, or memory.

42
00:02:14,555 --> 00:02:18,890
So if I spend an hour learning English, it's an investment.

43
00:02:18,850 --> 00:02:23,769
But if I spend an hour scrolling on my phone without thinking, it's just gone.

44
00:02:23,889 --> 00:02:24,890
Yes.

45
00:02:25,169 --> 00:02:30,890
And the more we see time this way, the more powerful our choices become.

46
00:02:31,654 --> 00:02:33,775
You're right.

47
00:02:33,975 --> 00:02:35,855
Time really is precious.

48
00:02:36,135 --> 00:02:38,095
I don't want to waste it anymore.

49
00:02:38,055 --> 00:02:39,614
None of us do.

50
00:02:39,815 --> 00:02:42,655
And that's why this conversation matters.

51
00:02:42,854 --> 00:02:51,900
Because once we see the value of time, we can start to live more fully, more wisely, and more joyfully.

52
00:02:52,180 --> 00:02:57,260
Daniel, in the last section, we talked about time as treasure.

53
00:02:57,380 --> 00:03:00,780
But there's something even more delicate about time.

54
00:03:01,265 --> 00:03:02,585
Our youth.

55
00:03:03,825 --> 00:03:04,825
Youth.

56
00:03:05,025 --> 00:03:08,105
You mean being young, full of energy?

57
00:03:08,625 --> 00:03:09,545
Exactly.

58
00:03:09,665 --> 00:03:11,465
Youth is a gift.

59
00:03:11,665 --> 00:03:14,345
When we're young, we think we have endless time.

60
00:03:14,790 --> 00:03:17,530
We believe our bodies will always be strong.

61
00:03:17,530 --> 00:03:19,790
Our energy will always return.

62
00:03:20,309 --> 00:03:23,710
But the truth is youth doesn't last forever.

63
00:03:24,150 --> 00:03:26,110
That makes me a little sad.

64
00:03:26,389 --> 00:03:31,735
Because sometimes I do feel young, but other times, I already feel tired.

65
00:03:31,695 --> 00:03:33,095
That's natural.

66
00:03:33,294 --> 00:03:35,174
And it's not about fear.

67
00:03:35,374 --> 00:03:37,255
It's about awareness.

68
00:03:38,014 --> 00:03:42,294
When we're aware that youth is limited, we can use it wisely.

69
00:03:42,590 --> 00:03:44,849
You know, I remember when I was a teenager,

70
00:03:44,849 --> 00:03:46,370
I could stay up all night,

71
00:03:46,370 --> 00:03:49,590
eat junk food, and still feel fine the next morning.

72
00:03:49,710 --> 00:03:53,350
Now even one late night makes me feel like a zombie.

73
00:03:53,310 --> 00:03:54,530
Yes.

74
00:03:54,530 --> 00:03:56,470
That's such a clear reminder.

75
00:03:57,014 --> 00:04:00,735
Our bodies change, and our energy changes too.

76
00:04:01,255 --> 00:04:05,295
That's why wasting time becomes more costly as we grow older.

77
00:04:05,415 --> 00:04:10,155
So you're saying we should take advantage of our energy while we still have it?

78
00:04:10,155 --> 00:04:10,734
Exactly.

79
00:04:11,230 --> 00:04:14,470
Not in a pressured way, but in a grateful way.

80
00:04:14,830 --> 00:04:17,670
Youth is a season, like spring.

81
00:04:18,109 --> 00:04:20,390
Flowers don't bloom forever.

82
00:04:20,589 --> 00:04:24,310
But while they bloom, they bring beauty and life.

83
00:04:24,750 --> 00:04:26,230
That's a beautiful picture.

84
00:04:26,955 --> 00:04:32,515
But, Emma, isn't it also true that people can do meaningful things even when they're older?

85
00:04:33,114 --> 00:04:34,195
Of course.

86
00:04:34,795 --> 00:04:37,235
Every age has its own strength,

87
00:04:37,275 --> 00:04:40,895
but youth is special because it gives us extra energy

88
00:04:40,895 --> 00:04:43,370
and courage to build a foundation.

89
00:04:43,890 --> 00:04:49,370
For example, learning languages, starting habits, or developing skills.

90
00:04:49,730 --> 00:04:52,890
They all grow easier when you start earlier.

91
00:04:53,490 --> 00:04:54,330
I see.

92
00:04:54,854 --> 00:04:58,875
So if I waste my youth only on entertainment or laziness,

93
00:04:58,875 --> 00:05:02,175
I might regret it later when I don't have the same energy.

94
00:05:02,375 --> 00:05:03,375
Yes.

95
00:05:03,734 --> 00:05:05,535
And regret is heavy.

96
00:05:05,814 --> 00:05:08,815
That's why awareness now is so powerful.

97
00:05:09,219 --> 00:05:14,220
It lets us use youth as a blessing instead of letting it slip away.

98
00:05:14,900 --> 00:05:17,019
I think I needed this reminder.

99
00:05:17,219 --> 00:05:20,120
Sometimes I tell myself, I'll do it later.

100
00:05:20,120 --> 00:05:21,100
I have time.

101
00:05:21,379 --> 00:05:24,859
But maybe I don't have as much time as I think.

102
00:05:25,304 --> 00:05:26,465
Exactly.

103
00:05:26,664 --> 00:05:30,225
That little voice, I'll do it later, is dangerous.

104
00:05:30,505 --> 00:05:33,805
Later may come, but youth may not wait.

105
00:05:33,805 --> 00:05:35,105
That hits me.

106
00:05:35,465 --> 00:05:38,305
Maybe I should start now, not tomorrow.

107
00:05:38,344 --> 00:05:39,345
Yes, Daniel.

108
00:05:39,770 --> 00:05:46,130
And to our listeners, maybe you can ask yourselves, what is one thing I've been waiting to start?

109
00:05:46,250 --> 00:05:49,810
Can I begin today while I still have energy?

110
00:05:49,770 --> 00:05:51,010
That's powerful.

111
00:05:51,289 --> 00:05:57,435
Youth isn't endless, but if we use it well, its impact can last a lifetime.

112
00:05:57,554 --> 00:05:58,954
Beautifully said.

113
00:05:59,075 --> 00:06:03,915
Youth is not forever, but what you do with it can echo forever.

114
00:06:05,090 --> 00:06:10,890
Daniel, we've talked about time as treasure and how youth doesn't last forever.

115
00:06:11,250 --> 00:06:15,030
But there's another challenge we face today, distractions.

116
00:06:15,030 --> 00:06:16,250
Oh, yes.

117
00:06:16,289 --> 00:06:18,090
I know this one too well.

118
00:06:18,495 --> 00:06:21,015
My biggest enemy is my phone.

119
00:06:20,974 --> 00:06:26,595
I pick it up just to check one message, and suddenly, forty minutes have disappeared.

120
00:06:26,595 --> 00:06:27,495
Exactly.

121
00:06:28,974 --> 00:06:30,535
Distractions are sneaky.

122
00:06:30,939 --> 00:06:33,360
They don't take whole days at once.

123
00:06:33,360 --> 00:06:35,380
They steal little pieces.

124
00:06:35,659 --> 00:06:41,300
Ten minutes here, half an hour there, until suddenly the whole day is gone.

125
00:06:42,859 --> 00:06:46,419
And the worst part is I don't even feel good after.

126
00:06:46,775 --> 00:06:52,095
I just feel empty, like I wasted my energy on nothing.

127
00:06:52,375 --> 00:06:53,295
Yes.

128
00:06:53,414 --> 00:06:54,815
That's the trap.

129
00:06:54,935 --> 00:07:00,255
Distractions give us the illusion of pleasure, but they rarely give us real satisfaction.

130
00:07:01,120 --> 00:07:05,860
So, Emma, why do we fall into them so easily?

131
00:07:05,860 --> 00:07:10,520
I think because distractions are easy, and meaningful things are often harder.

132
00:07:10,960 --> 00:07:13,400
Watching videos feels effortless.

133
00:07:13,599 --> 00:07:18,015
Studying, working, creating, that takes focus.

134
00:07:18,374 --> 00:07:21,375
Our brains naturally choose the easy path.

135
00:07:21,895 --> 00:07:23,135
That's true.

136
00:07:23,335 --> 00:07:30,655
Sometimes, even when I plan to study, my hand just reaches for the phone, almost like a reflex.

137
00:07:31,299 --> 00:07:32,120
Yes.

138
00:07:32,120 --> 00:07:35,740
It becomes a habit, and habits are powerful.

139
00:07:35,940 --> 00:07:39,180
But the good news is we can build new ones.

140
00:07:39,219 --> 00:07:40,140
How?

141
00:07:40,340 --> 00:07:42,300
One way is awareness.

142
00:07:42,420 --> 00:07:44,920
When you notice yourself reaching for the phone,

143
00:07:44,920 --> 00:07:50,394
pause and ask, is this really how I want to spend my next twenty minutes?

144
00:07:50,835 --> 00:07:54,315
That question alone could save me a lot of time.

145
00:07:54,674 --> 00:07:55,595
Yes.

146
00:07:56,594 --> 00:07:58,634
Another way is replacement.

147
00:07:58,919 --> 00:08:04,480
Instead of only removing distractions, give yourself something meaningful to fill the space,

148
00:08:04,599 --> 00:08:08,300
like listening to a podcast, writing, or even resting.

149
00:08:08,300 --> 00:08:10,220
So it's not just about stopping.

150
00:08:10,220 --> 00:08:12,079
It's about choosing better.

151
00:08:12,200 --> 00:08:13,039
Exactly.

152
00:08:13,474 --> 00:08:16,555
And sometimes it helps to create little boundaries.

153
00:08:16,674 --> 00:08:19,995
For example, I don't keep my phone near my bed at night.

154
00:08:20,034 --> 00:08:23,915
That way, my mornings begin calm, not chaotic.

155
00:08:24,275 --> 00:08:27,114
Oh, I always check my phone first thing.

156
00:08:27,370 --> 00:08:29,790
No wonder my mornings feel messy.

157
00:08:29,790 --> 00:08:30,850
You see?

158
00:08:30,890 --> 00:08:33,650
Small changes can protect your time.

159
00:08:33,929 --> 00:08:35,810
It's strange, isn't it?

160
00:08:35,850 --> 00:08:41,970
We say we don't have time, but really, time is often hiding in the places we waste it.

161
00:08:42,505 --> 00:08:43,665
That's true.

162
00:08:43,625 --> 00:08:46,145
Distractions don't just steal time.

163
00:08:46,185 --> 00:08:48,624
They also steal opportunities.

164
00:08:48,745 --> 00:08:53,905
The chance to grow, to rest deeply, to connect with people we love.

165
00:08:54,730 --> 00:08:56,370
That makes me think.

166
00:08:56,650 --> 00:09:00,430
How many moments with family or with myself have I lost

167
00:09:00,430 --> 00:09:02,610
because I was staring at a screen?

168
00:09:03,050 --> 00:09:04,850
That's a powerful question.

169
00:09:05,130 --> 00:09:06,830
And it's not about guilt.

170
00:09:06,830 --> 00:09:07,810
It's about awareness.

171
00:09:08,354 --> 00:09:12,874
When we see the cost of distractions, we can begin to take back our time.

172
00:09:13,234 --> 00:09:14,155
Yes.

173
00:09:14,354 --> 00:09:17,195
And maybe listeners can ask themselves too.

174
00:09:17,234 --> 00:09:20,715
What's the biggest distraction in my life right now?

175
00:09:20,995 --> 00:09:23,915
And what small step can I take to reduce it?

176
00:09:24,490 --> 00:09:25,650
Exactly.

177
00:09:25,770 --> 00:09:30,530
Because when we free ourselves from distractions, we don't just save time.

178
00:09:30,650 --> 00:09:33,010
We give life back to ourselves.

179
00:09:33,530 --> 00:09:38,370
Daniel, once we notice distractions and how they steal our time,

180
00:09:38,824 --> 00:09:43,505
the next question is, what should we use that time for?

181
00:09:43,944 --> 00:09:44,865
Right.

182
00:09:45,064 --> 00:09:51,505
If I take away the phone, the videos, the endless scrolling, I suddenly have hours.

183
00:09:51,865 --> 00:09:56,150
But then I wonder, what do I actually want to do with them?

184
00:09:56,510 --> 00:09:58,630
That's the heart of the matter.

185
00:09:58,829 --> 00:10:01,350
Choosing what truly matters.

186
00:10:01,630 --> 00:10:05,270
Because time is limited, we can't do everything.

187
00:10:05,550 --> 00:10:08,710
But we can choose the things that give life meaning.

188
00:10:09,704 --> 00:10:15,425
That sounds beautiful, but also a little heavy.

189
00:10:15,625 --> 00:10:17,745
What if I choose the wrong things?

190
00:10:18,185 --> 00:10:22,385
That's a fair fear, but often the answer is simple.

191
00:10:22,424 --> 00:10:27,900
Ask yourself, what will I be glad I did when I look back a year from now?

192
00:10:28,020 --> 00:10:29,420
I like that.

193
00:10:29,780 --> 00:10:35,260
A year from now, I don't think I'll remember the hours I spent watching funny clips,

194
00:10:35,300 --> 00:10:38,860
but I'll remember the book I finished or the skill I learned.

195
00:10:39,314 --> 00:10:40,475
Exactly.

196
00:10:40,595 --> 00:10:46,315
Or the conversations you had, the people you helped, the memories you created.

197
00:10:46,595 --> 00:10:49,275
Those are the treasures that stay.

198
00:10:49,395 --> 00:10:50,455
It's true.

199
00:10:50,455 --> 00:10:53,115
Some of my happiest memories are really simple.

200
00:10:53,314 --> 00:10:58,810
Playing guitar with a friend, cooking dinner with my mom, or just taking a long walk.

201
00:10:58,850 --> 00:10:59,850
Yes.

202
00:11:00,209 --> 00:11:03,530
What matters most is often not complicated.

203
00:11:03,729 --> 00:11:07,210
It's the things that connect us to ourselves and to others.

204
00:11:08,265 --> 00:11:11,345
But, Emma, sometimes I feel pressure.

205
00:11:11,465 --> 00:11:16,545
Everyone says, do something big, be successful, make money.

206
00:11:16,665 --> 00:11:19,744
How do I know if what matters to me is enough?

207
00:11:20,980 --> 00:11:22,540
That's a deep question.

208
00:11:22,900 --> 00:11:26,060
I believe what matters is deeply personal.

209
00:11:26,420 --> 00:11:29,500
For one person, it may be building a business.

210
00:11:29,780 --> 00:11:32,860
For another, it's raising children with love.

211
00:11:33,220 --> 00:11:35,500
For another, it's creating art.

212
00:11:36,255 --> 00:11:41,495
What matters is not how the world measures it, but how your heart feels it.

213
00:11:42,015 --> 00:11:44,935
So meaning isn't always loud.

214
00:11:45,055 --> 00:11:46,695
Sometimes it's quiet.

215
00:11:47,215 --> 00:11:47,895
Exactly.

216
00:11:48,550 --> 00:11:50,990
And here's something I ask myself.

217
00:11:51,270 --> 00:11:54,430
Does this give me life, or does it drain me?

218
00:11:54,790 --> 00:11:59,310
If it gives me life, even if it's small, then it matters.

219
00:11:59,910 --> 00:12:00,750
I see.

220
00:12:01,145 --> 00:12:05,405
That means even something like practicing English for twenty minutes matters

221
00:12:05,405 --> 00:12:08,065
because it connects me to my future self.

222
00:12:08,025 --> 00:12:08,845
Yes.

223
00:12:08,845 --> 00:12:10,145
Perfectly said.

224
00:12:10,265 --> 00:12:15,425
Every small act that builds love, growth, or connection has value.

225
00:12:16,090 --> 00:12:22,930
You know, this makes me want to make a little list of what truly matters to me right now just to keep it clear.

226
00:12:23,449 --> 00:12:25,410
That's a wonderful idea.

227
00:12:25,610 --> 00:12:28,129
And to our listeners, maybe you can do the same.

228
00:12:28,574 --> 00:12:32,375
Write down three things that matter most to you this season.

229
00:12:32,815 --> 00:12:36,935
Then ask yourself, am I giving them my best hours?

230
00:12:37,135 --> 00:12:41,495
That's a little scary, but also exciting.

231
00:12:41,535 --> 00:12:42,855
It is.

232
00:12:43,420 --> 00:12:47,780
Because when you choose what truly matters, you don't just save time.

233
00:12:47,980 --> 00:12:51,220
You create a life worth remembering.

234
00:12:52,540 --> 00:12:58,260
Daniel, we've spoken about time, youth, distractions, and choosing what matters.

235
00:12:58,885 --> 00:13:05,645
Now comes the final piece, how to live with both urgency and joy.

236
00:13:06,005 --> 00:13:07,965
Urgency and joy?

237
00:13:08,324 --> 00:13:10,445
Those sound almost opposite.

238
00:13:10,724 --> 00:13:14,285
Urgency feels like pressure, and joy feels like freedom.

239
00:13:15,120 --> 00:13:17,000
That's true.

240
00:13:17,040 --> 00:13:21,320
But when they come together, they create a powerful way to live.

241
00:13:21,920 --> 00:13:25,320
Urgency means remembering life is short.

242
00:13:25,920 --> 00:13:28,920
Joy means celebrating life as a gift.

243
00:13:30,065 --> 00:13:31,045
I see.

244
00:13:31,045 --> 00:13:36,425
So urgency wakes us up, and joy keeps us alive while we're awake.

245
00:13:37,105 --> 00:13:38,105
Exactly.

246
00:13:38,225 --> 00:13:40,665
Without urgency, we waste time.

247
00:13:41,279 --> 00:13:43,960
Without joy, we suffer through it.

248
00:13:44,159 --> 00:13:48,200
But with both, every day becomes precious.

249
00:13:49,279 --> 00:13:51,720
That makes me think of my grandfather.

250
00:13:51,839 --> 00:13:55,400
He always told me, don't wait too long to live.

251
00:13:55,895 --> 00:13:58,415
Tomorrow is never promised.

252
00:13:59,255 --> 00:14:00,575
Wise words.

253
00:14:00,775 --> 00:14:04,655
And yet many of us live as if tomorrow is guaranteed.

254
00:14:04,775 --> 00:14:07,455
We say, I'll call my friend later.

255
00:14:07,415 --> 00:14:09,295
I'll start my dream next year.

256
00:14:10,030 --> 00:14:12,530
But life doesn't always wait.

257
00:14:12,530 --> 00:14:13,670
That's true.

258
00:14:13,790 --> 00:14:15,750
I lost a friend last year,

259
00:14:16,030 --> 00:14:20,950
and I remember thinking I should have spent more time with him when I had the chance.

260
00:14:21,230 --> 00:14:22,790
I'm sorry, Daniel.

261
00:14:22,829 --> 00:14:24,550
That's a painful reminder.

262
00:14:24,974 --> 00:14:28,455
But it also shows us why urgency matters,

263
00:14:28,414 --> 00:14:32,855
not to scare us, but to remind us to love and act today.

264
00:14:32,974 --> 00:14:34,135
And joy.

265
00:14:34,495 --> 00:14:36,295
How do we bring that in?

266
00:14:36,734 --> 00:14:40,614
Joy comes when we notice the simple gifts of the present moment.

267
00:14:41,340 --> 00:14:48,180
Drinking tea, hearing laughter, learning something new, walking in the sun.

268
00:14:48,380 --> 00:14:53,379
These moments when lived fully make urgency gentle, not heavy.

269
00:14:53,795 --> 00:14:57,755
So urgency tells me, don't waste this moment.

270
00:14:57,715 --> 00:15:01,495
And joy tells me, enjoy this moment.

271
00:15:01,495 --> 00:15:02,395
Yes.

272
00:15:02,755 --> 00:15:06,075
Together, they make life meaningful and beautiful.

273
00:15:06,840 --> 00:15:10,800
You know, Emma, I think I've often lived with neither.

274
00:15:11,160 --> 00:15:14,000
Sometimes I waste time without urgency.

275
00:15:14,359 --> 00:15:16,879
Other times, I work hard without joy.

276
00:15:17,160 --> 00:15:19,439
But now, I want both.

277
00:15:20,125 --> 00:15:23,045
And that's the invitation for all of us,

278
00:15:23,405 --> 00:15:25,765
to live as if time is precious

279
00:15:25,885 --> 00:15:29,125
and to love as if every moment is a gift.

280
00:15:30,125 --> 00:15:35,970
That makes me feel grateful right now, just sitting here, having this conversation.

281
00:15:36,650 --> 00:15:38,130
Me too, Daniel.

282
00:15:38,650 --> 00:15:47,330
And to our listeners, maybe you can ask, what is one way I can live today with urgency and joy?

283
00:15:48,664 --> 00:15:51,504
I'll start by calling my mom tonight.

284
00:15:51,704 --> 00:15:54,705
That feels both urgent and joyful.

285
00:15:54,664 --> 00:15:58,064
That's perfect, and I think she'll be very happy.

286
00:15:59,304 --> 00:16:01,825
As we close, let's take a moment together.

287
00:16:02,640 --> 00:16:04,040
Time is passing.

288
00:16:04,160 --> 00:16:06,200
Youth is not forever.

289
00:16:06,560 --> 00:16:11,560
Distractions are always near, but you have the power to choose.

290
00:16:11,840 --> 00:16:14,280
You can give your hours to what matters.

291
00:16:14,725 --> 00:16:18,525
And when we do, we don't just fill time.

292
00:16:18,564 --> 00:16:23,645
We live it fully, urgently, and joyfully.

293
00:16:23,925 --> 00:16:24,845
Yes.

294
00:16:25,045 --> 00:16:28,850
So, dear friends, maybe tonight or tomorrow morning,

295
00:16:28,850 --> 00:16:34,230
pause and ask yourself, am I living the life I want to remember?

296
00:16:34,829 --> 00:16:38,070
Thank you, Emma, and thank you, listeners.

297
00:16:38,190 --> 00:16:40,150
Let's not waste our time.

298
00:16:40,270 --> 00:16:41,830
We're not young forever.

299
00:16:42,475 --> 00:16:46,675
Take care of your moments, and they will take care of you.

300
00:16:47,194 --> 00:16:50,835
We'll see you next time here on the Cozy English.

301
00:16:51,035 --> 00:16:55,615
Bye, everyone, and don't forget to live today.
